We need to “extract” all the transactions that belong to the Interest Receivable account (the rows whose “type” is “Interest Receivables”) and then “add‐up” their amounts. In many bookkeeping systems the beginning balance is from a prior period (here no “Interest receivable” appears on the initial entry) so we assume an opening balance of 0.00. Then all the “Interest Receivables” entries increase the balance. (In our case each row “Interest… ” is recorded with a positive amount, and none are “paid”, so they all remain “receivables.”)

Step 2. (Compute the total final balance)

Let’s add them in groups. (You can do the sum using more exact numbers, but here rounding to two decimals will yield the same answer when rounded to two decimals.)

• First three rows: 411.93 + 408.82 + 408.82 ≈ 1229.57  
• Next two rows (rows 4–5): 357.02 + 357.02 ≈ 714.04  
• Row 6: 335.64  
• Rows 7–13: There are 7 entries each about 316.42 so 7×316.42 ≈ 2214.94  
• Rows 14–16: Three entries each about 243.37 so 3×243.37 ≈ 730.11  
• Rows 17–32: There are 16 entries each about 240.16 so 16×240.16 ≈ 3842.56

Now add these groups:

• 1229.57 + 714.04 = 1943.61  
• 1943.61 + 335.64 = 2279.25  
• 2279.25 + 2214.94 ≈ 4494.19  
• 4494.19 + 730.11 ≈ 5224.30  
• 5224.30 + 3842.56 ≈ 9066.86

So the total “Interest Receivable” balance at the end of the period is about 9066.86.

Step 3. (Setting the initial balance)

Because no interest receivable appears among the “Initial…” entries, we assume an initial balance of zero.

Thus, the answer will be:
